column40: How DACL can tie to grading
column48: The original planning date was postponed due to weather. Via an email I was notified as to the topic the the HS BLT wanted to address. The district admin team is doing a book study on "15 Fixes for Broken Grades" by O'Connor. They are considering SBG and wanted to know how this might tie with DACL... The team discussed how the MMD practices can be used as a direct tie. examples: 13. Don’t use information from formative assessments and practice to determine grades; use only summative	evidence. This is tied to CFA and the practice of changing instruction not grades. 15. Don’t leave students out of the grading process. Involve	students; they can - and should - play key roles in assessment and grading that promote 	achievement. Tied to DACL and involving the students in the classroom practices. This discussion helped to draw in the teachers to wanting to have a deeper understanding and usage of DACL - especially learning targets and success criteria. This is the topic for the next all day BLT meeting.

column28: planning identification and use of essential standards and I Can statements
column48: This meeting was scheduled to determine how each building would work with essential standards and "I can" statements in preparation for deeper work with DACL.  After a review of what had been developed previously, they realized most grade levels were not in alignment with the Missouri Learning Standards.  As a result, "I can" statements and CFAs were not in alignment.  This oversight needs to be rectified.  The meeting was held with all district administrators in attendance, and a plan was developed that will move each building forward from where their teachers and curriculum are currently.

column28: "I can" statements; Essential Standards
column47: Essential Standards identified by the district; "I can" statements list
column48: This district has begun work with DACL and come to the realization that they need to work with and complete their Essential Standards and at least a preliminary list of "I can" statements which can be used in classrooms.  The Elementary classes are using a standards-based report card and have worked the past few years to identify their essential standards and to incorporate those into their report card statements.  The Middle School and High School are working in vertical teams in each building to ensure they have identified their Essential Standards. All teachers are involved in this work including Special Education and specials teachers. They determined that while not all "I can" statements can be prepared in advance, some critical thoughts are being prepared so their work with DACL can continue.  Identifying these will also allow them to ensure their CFAs reflect the critical work of the classroom.
column50: Work in grade-span groups to review essential standards and to identify gaps

column28: "I can" statements in each content area; identified gaps in content areas
column48: Five members of Cadre 1 traveled to Brookfield to work with teachers as they reviewed standards, wrote appropriate "I can" statements, discussed CFAs and cleaned up their work prior to starting a deeper dive into DACL in the near future.  Each consultant worked with one content area for 90 minutes.  Following the work with the teachers, the consultants met with the principals.  We discussed the progress being made, where they were struggling, and then offered suggestions on next steps for each area.  Not every content area can be completed exactly as the others, so discussing the areas in conflict was also included.  The next meeting was scheduled for March 6, but after reflection the principals made a decision to put that meeting off to give the teachers more time to complete their alignment and to prepare their "I can" statements.  The need to prepare CFAs that reflect their "I can" statements was discussed.

column48:
Because this was an introductory meeting, we covered DCI in some detail.  I began by having each building complete the Implementation Survey, as the buildings are in different places and have had different trainings.  From there, we discussed their goals as a district.  Two of the buildings discussed the need to work on Collaborative Teams because they have not worked well together in the past but hope to change that with new administrators.  One of the buildings wants to focus on alignment as they have noted their teachers are teaching everything in the book whether it's an expectation or not.  Differentiation is another area they want to pursue.

I talked with them in depth about the VLP and then isolated each of the modules to introduce them briefly.  It was determined that DBDM will probably be the place most of the buildings want to start.  CFA is another area of interest at this time.

We left the meeting with the idea that the administrators would access the VLP at a meeting they will have so they can get in and see what the modules look like.  At that point, they will make contact and we will begin planning the logistics of providing assistance to their district.

column36: Review of CWIS data
column48:
The Clark County DLT met in conjunction with a planned administrators' meeting.  All building level administrators were present and one assistant administrator.  The purpose of the meeting was to review CWIS data and to discuss challenges getting the VLP on all staff computers.  

On the CWIS, it was noted that only the Middle School had a lower response than anticipated with 11 staff members completing the survey.  A short period of time was provided for them to review their data.  It was noted that the statements regarding the Effective Teaching and Learning Practices had the most areas of concern.  Of particular interest were the following statements:  Learning Targets, Students Assessing their progress, Students Identify next steps, and Students State Success Criteria.  It was noted that in the Middle School, all areas of the Data-Based Decision Making were a concern but it must be pointed out that only 11 had completed the survey from the Middle School, and of those only 2 responded to the questions about DBDM.  Further information is needed before next steps can be planned for this building.  

After review of the data, it was determined that the DLT have additional time to study and review the data before making a decision on next steps.

Newly hired ESSA support was discussed.  It was noted that Kelly O'Laughlin will be joining the team in the future.

Prior to the meeting, steps for assigning the SAPP to all staff members was discussed with the superintendent.  Additional support from Edwin Hall was very helpful.  Their goal is to get everyone access to the web apps and then to VLP during their professional development meeting in the following week.

column48:
After discussion, it was determined that Clark County would begin their journey with the Data Based Decision Making module.  Embedded in that will be some initial introduction to the use of formative assessments.  There will be two training groups formed.  One will include the appropriate members of the Early Childhood/Behavioral Center, Black Hawk Elementary, and Running Fox Elementary.  The other will be formed of teachers from the Middle School and High School.  The training will take place on April 27, 2020 from 8:15 to 11:15 in Black Hawk Elementary and at the High School.

Other work was considered and discussed.  At the Early Childhood Center, it was reported that they are trying to rework the Care Team process to meet their needs.  They are also attempting to support curriculum at K-2 and working with Fundations and touch math.  Black Hawk Elementary is focusing on curriculum alignment with teachers currently working independently in ELA.  Running Fox is working to align curriculum in the transitional grades, i.e. 2nd - 3rd to make sure there are no gaps.  They are also focusing on data driven instruction.  The High School is exploring a move to Study Island for the 2020-21 school year.  It was noted that the Middle School does not have Title I services.  They reportedly need a more accessible curriculum and need assistance diversifying instruction, as most of their teachers are content-based and not specifically trained in Middle School teaching.

We also discussed having the RPDC Special Ed team work with the district on differentiation with follow-up coaching being done by the DCI team.  Currently, no final decisions have been made.

column28: Observing  classrooms and their teaching practices
column48: We conducted a walk-through of the elementary buildings in the district to see what practices were in place, to determine if daily targets were being utilized, and to look for signs of differentiation.  While a few of the teachers did have their targets posted, most did not.  A variety of teaching strategies were observed but not specifically for differentiation.  This was an initial observation prior the the planning session for the work to begin next fall.  This district is in the early stages of DCI and have committed to a more concerted effort next year, with DCI being part of the PD planning discussion.  At this time, they are discussing starting with collaborative teams, DBDM, and/or differentiation in conjunction with the RPDC Special Ed team.  We spent approximately 20 minutes in each room.

column28: Observing for learning targets posted in classrooms, teaching practices
column48: Our goal in the two buildings today was to complete walk-throughs of the final district buildings, watching for the use of learning targets, observing instructional strategies, and becoming familiar with the teachers and buildings.  District personnel have had no formal training in DACL, so the expectation of learning targets was not as high as if that training had been completed.  While a few had posted learning targets, most had not.  The district came into the DCI process after having buildings identified as focus buildings.  As a result, PD days had already been planned and most of our interactions with district administrators have involved discussions of DCI and planning.  At this time, the Superintendent has indicated they are actively planning to include DCI in their PD days next school year and they are meetings to determine where to start.  Collaborative teams, DBDM, and differentiation have been discussed.

column28: Building walk-through with DACL sheet
column48: The purpose of the day was to do a whole-building walk-through of each classroom using the DACL observation sheet. I used the shortened version developed for use at Hayti because it lends itself to greater focus.  I spent at least 15 minutes in each classroom, making notes on the observation sheet while I was in the classroom.  All teachers were visited; after the data was collected I created a simple consolidation of the data in order to report the results during the after-school meeting. Overall the results were positive; even though it was a short pre-Thanksgiving break, work continued as usual on this Monday.  I was able to with with a table of teachers during the first part of the meeting as K-2 processed their benchmark data that they had graded. I then shared the results of the walk-through with the entire group with comments about celebrations and low areas.  (Part of this was due to the short week and not having a full week's plans to complete.)

column39: State assessment preparation
column48: Teachers spent the first part of the meeting on preparations for the upcoming state assessments, so I waited through that section. This building keeps data on several assessments, so by the time for state assessments, they can accurately predict student performance, unless there is some extenuating circumstance in the home, etc.  They make a prediction and then check it against actual student performance on the state assessment. Assessment is triangulated and examined across the school year. Data teams then met to review the final formative results for the academic year. Teachers are always encouraged to bring examples of engaging instructional strategies to share at these meetings. Data teams were looking for growth, not just attainment of a particular score. There were several examples of K-2 students showing growth on this assessment, which was a very positive result. Teachers also discussed ways to build a vertical progression of writing skills and performance.  Staff generally agreed that they need to narrow their focus for the next school year to DACL and coaching. They felt they had tried to do too many different things this year.

A brief overview of the DCI process and work were given, followed by the CO staff talking about their strategic plan and how this work aligned with that plan.  Next the group developed their own norms for this group, as well as what consensus protocol they would use for decision-making.  The Collaborative Work SAPP observation sheet gave them a chance to self-assessment this group using the tool.  Next we crossed their thoughts over to the Collaborative Work Practice Profile, which they marked as a team where they felt that they were in each Essential Function.  They also set some goals for improvement.  Lastly, they walked through the Leadership Practice Profile and again talked about where they needed to focus for growth.

column48:
We met with Stephanie Utterback, asst. principal, to have discussions about where they are in their current implementation of the modules. Entire building took SAPPs to drive PDPs. Entire math, ELA, and science departments have Learning Targets and Proficiency Scales for ALL standards. SS in working on theirs'. 
     Agendas are developed in a Google form for each team to see and use to keep minutes. The building is using a SWIVL for coaching. Building data have guided them to determine intervention areas. They are not only comparing MAP data in district and building, but also across several other like-size districts. 
     We, also, took a tour of the building and observed a few classrooms. Bulletin boards are up in each hallway with grade-level data with goals and growth for math and ELA. Learning targets were up in classrooms.
     The two lead people (Stephanie and their Instructional Coach, Melinda Kneib) are good at studying and going deeper with PD. This building is far ahead of the other buildings.

column48: This was the district-wide 3rd grade team meeting. They are currently working on developing assessments wrapped around the standards. The next two standards will be completed between this meeting and the next. The first thing they discussed today was pacing. Then they were given the protocol for how they were going to begin working on developing the next two items: understanding fractions and comparing fractions. The teams were divided by building with the two smaller buildings that usually work together as one team. Team 1 will look for DOK 1 questions, Team 2 will look for DOK 2 & 3 questions, Team 3 will look for tech enhanced questions. These three teams will submit to team 4. Team 4 will select items to determine and assessment, put into the Google folder for all to view and submit any questions. At the next meeting the teams will rotate and they will work on the next two standards. Hannibal hopes to have all of math completed by the end of the year. They will try to find time this summer to complete English.

This was the monthly Elementary DLT meeting. The main purpose of the meeting was to update them up on VLP, invoices, and Spring CWIS dates. Some were not aware the District folder has information that will help them to make decisions. For example, I shared that areas not previously marked on Invoices 1 & 2 could still be marked and that a summary was in the folder, also that the Google Slides with links I was using was in the folder. I gave them the link to the folder in the chat. 
     Some are still having difficulties with the VLP and asked me to set up a zoom meeting to address some of them. Kelly has met with some, if not all, of them, and they seemed embarrassed to set up another date with her. I set up a zoom and invited Kelly. Shared that they cannot see team reports until the team has closed it.   
     Shawn (District Contact) said he would send the CWIS link when he received it. He will set a shorter time to take it, most likely within a week. The admin CWIS link was shared. This will tell them the number who have completed for their building. If they have difficulty, the CST can get the information.
Priority Standards have been chosen for all content areas. Math CFAs are being developed for those priorities. Expectation is to have them done by the end of the school year. This may take a few days in the summer.

column38: As this was an introductory/planning session, the Implementation Plan was completed and discussed.  The principal shared goals for the district, including work with differentiated instruction and possible co-teaching.  She also noted that curriculum work needs to be a strong consideration as some of their books are several years old and have not been aligned to the MLS.  This is a 4-day week district.  While she noted that Collaborative Teams need to be worked with and strengthened and that DBDM needs to be taught and coached, her three goals were (1) alignment to MLS; (2) Priority Standards need to be identified; (3) a Pacing Guide needs to be created for K-5.  Some of these areas need to be completed prior to work with setting learning targets and goals, developing formative assessments, and determining effective teaching and learning strategies.  It was noted that the district met their goal during last spring's testing as required by their targeted school status.

As this was an introductory/planning session, the Implementation Plan was completed and discussed.  The principal shared goals for the district, including work with differentiated instruction and possible co-teaching.  She also noted that curriculum work needs to be a strong consideration as some of their books are several years old and have not been aligned to the MLS.  This is a 4-day week district.  While she noted that Collaborative Teams need to be worked with and strengthened and that DBDM needs to be taught and coached, her three goals were (1) alignment to MLS; (2) Priority Standards need to be identified; (3) a Pacing Guide needs to be created for K-5.  Some of these areas need to be completed prior to work with setting learning targets and goals, developing formative assessments, and determining effective teaching and learning strategies.  It was noted that the district met their goal during last spring's testing as required by their targeted school status.  

This principal has been with the district two years.  She reported that they have begun using iReady at the K-5 level.  She also noted that while they have had training in some of the areas discussed, new staff has resulted in the need for introductory levels of training.  At this time, she is making the final decisions for her District Leadership Team, encouraging her teachers to complete the CWIS by October 9, and reviewing the modules as she considers first steps.

column48:
This was the first meeting with the newly formed DLT.  The principal has selected two teachers to sit on the team.  One is a fourth grade teacher and the other is an upper level special education teacher.  Because this was the first team meeting, much of the time was spent providing an overview of DCI, reviewing the Implementation Plan completed by the principal at the previous meeting, and discussing the need to get everyone on the VLP.  Time was spent reviewing the CWIS data, which all of the teachers completed, and discussing the evidence found there.  It was noted that the district indicated the use of learning targets was low across the district.  We also went through each module and I provided the graphic that introduced each.  This district uses STAR for Reading and Math assessment at the elementary and discussed the possibility of extending this into the high school.  Time was spent discussing the need to provide students more opportunities to engage with non-fiction, especially in science and social studies.  Determining their priority standards and then aligning them to learning targets is a priority.  They also want to focus this year on differentiation and Data Teams.  Discussion ensued on keeping notes of the meetings where they would be available to all staff members and it was determined they would use Google Classroom.  

The immediate plan is to get everyone access to the VLP by having them register for a DESE web app and then to encourage them to explore the VLP.

column48: The purpose of this meeting was to review the SAPP data for DACL and to determine goals for 2020.  SAPP data showed that most teachers rated themselves as a 1 for Essential Function 1 but gave themselves a rating of 4 for Essential Function 3.  The principal questioned these ratings but for now this is the data we are using for planning.  Possible ways to use the DACL module were discussed.  The principal stated she would go through the module on VLP over the holiday break and then make suggestions on how she felt the teachers would best respond to the training.  Walk-throughs were discussed but it was determined those should wait until the training starts and then walk-through to see how teachers are implementing the steps as they are introduced.

column28: I can statements
column48:
The purpose of this meeting was to touch base after the holidays to determine next steps in presenting DACL to the staff.   The principal stated she had reviewed the Introduction, reviewing all videos, activities, etc.  She noted that her first thought was that it was a lot for the staff to work with at this time.  She stated just that part took her 1.5 hours and that the teachers would state lack of time -- both personal and professional -- to be able to start this now.  She felt the videos were good and that the information was great, but she noted that the teachers would not know why this was being required of them.

Suggestion was made and accepted to focus this semester on the initial steps that must be in place prior to DACL being instituted.  They will require teachers to use and discuss "I can" statements with their students and the consultants will conduct classroom walk-throughs to make a general determination on how that work is progressing.  In addition, the practice profile will be used for feedback reflection and formative assessments will be noted.  In the meantime, the DLT will ensure that teachers are aware as to the plans the district has to incorporate DACL into the 20-21 school year.

The thought is to have different people present DACL to the staff on their PD days beginning next fall and to provide coaching to each teacher as needed.  Because of the walk-throughs focusing on ELA at the elementary level, the DLT was asked to provide schedules to the Consultants.  They were asked to provide those in the next week.  At the middle school/high school levels schedules will be provided where needed, otherwise consultants may go into any classroom.

column48: A review of the Self-Assessment Score Report indicated that the majority of the teachers rated themselves as a "1" of EF 1, "Where am I going?".  This was a walk through to look for evidence of EF 1 prior to starting the formal training/review of DACL.  Every classroom, except the Special Education resource rooms, were visited from 20 - 30 minutes each.  A large number of rooms had "I can" statements posted but the statements were not discussed with students in the majority of cases.  I personally did not hear any referred to during the time I was in the room, but not being in every room at the beginning of class does not allow me to say that no one was introducing those to students.  Kelly indicated that most of her classes also had the statements posted and that in at least one case the students were aware of where the statements were located.

column48: Higbee spent first semester preparing to begin work with the Developing Assessment Capable Learners module by working with their curriculum, meeting to develop an understanding of the DCI process, and beginning the writing of "I can" statements throughout the district.  At the previous meeting, the principal shared observations from a review of the DACL overview.  The purpose of this meeting was to make some decisions on how this module would be shared with teachers.  A recent walk-through of the classrooms had shown that, while a majority of the rooms had "I can" statements posted, they were not being explained or referred back to during the course of a class period.  The decision was made to begin by focusing on EF1 and to take small steps so teachers are not overwhelmed.  They also want teachers to understand that this is not something new being required, but is just a new way of thinking about talking with students.  The goal of the DLT is to have everyone writing and posting "I can" statements by the beginning of the 2020-21 school year.  Transparency with teachers is a critical piece and when they meet with teachers they want to share basic information and goals.  They would also like all teachers to begin collecting examples of strong and weak work that can be used with students during the coming year.  The DLT will plan the introductory presentation based on the information presented in the module on the VLP.

column48: Training was provided on the last two questions of DACL.  I did the elementary training and Chelsea did the training with the secondary teachers.  I had provided training on the first question (DACL) for the entire district prior to school starting.  We are following backward design with this district.  Their three year goal is DACL.  However, in the planning meeting at the end of last year, it was determined that their teachers or administrators really didn't know what that looked like and sounded like in the classroom.  Since there wasn't much progress in this district last year, the plan was made to help them visualize their goal and then perhaps they would see the need for some foundational work to be done.  This has certainly proved to be true.  The instructional coaches are systematically working through the CFA work with all grade levels and courses in the district throughout this year. It is a collaborative process.  CSTs are providing coaching support for the coaches as needed.  The Director of Instruction sent me a copy of their schedule with this work for the year.  It represents a consistent, systematic plan.  I am getting positive feedback.  The high school principal told me that one of his most respected math teachers told him that this is the first time that he can remember when he felt like the work the teams were doing was going to make a difference.  The principal said this teacher's feedback carried a lot of weight with him.

column40: Notes from the meeting
column48:
We met with each building administrator (elementary, middle, and high) individually to plan specific support for their building for the year.  This followed a full day in the district meeting with each building's leadership team and ending the day meeting with the district MMD team to create a three year plan.  

High School: The high school principal has already began implementing a process for deepening the DBDM process with his teachers.  He used data from the SAPP to provide the focus. They are using the practice profile rubric to monitor their progress. We shared the VLP with the principal and suggested his teachers use this as deemed necessary. This work is leading the teachers to question the rigor of their assessments (considered a good thing).  The tentative plan is to check back with the principal in a few weeks and most likely provide some training with the CFA module second semester.  We are looking at dates for this work.  

Middle School: The middle school is focusing on collaborative teams.  They have considerable work to do in this area, but most of the intensity of the work will most likely be in the first essential function.  The leadership team (with the guidance of the principal) have already been working on a schedule and structure of the collaborative meetings.  We explained the VLP to the principal.  The plan is for the leadership team to decide exactly how the VLP might be most effectively used during their next PD day.  They will use the practice profile rubric to monitor their progress.  We will be checking in with the principal in the next couple of weeks for an update.

Elementary:  This principal is already hard at work with her teachers to strengthen collaborative teams and the DBDM process.  They have determined some weak links in their curriculum in the area of reading that they are addressing heading-on.  The instructional coach is playing a major part in this work.  We explained the VLP to the principal, but at this time suggested that they continue what they are doing while using the practice profile to monitor their work.  We will be staying in touch.
column49: Future dates have not been determined at this time.  However,  we are in the process of looking at dates with each building.

column48: Liz and I were able to observe three grade level teams (K, 4, 5) as they met with the principal and other interventionist in the building to discuss their at-risk students. (We will observe the other grade level meeting on February 20th.)The purpose of the meeting is to review progress (academic and behavioral) for each targeted student and revise interventions as needed.  All teams followed the agreed upon protocol for the meeting.  The principal recorded detailed notes on each student discussed and teachers will enter update information on the individual data collection sheet that serves as a running record from one grade level to the next.  The principal asked for feedback during a break. We were able to share several positives about the meeting: respectful, timely, followed agenda and protocol, the principal and all interventionists involvement on a regular basis, on-going records. Our suggested opportunity for growth was to base their decisions on specific data.  The principal was very receptive and agreed that  was an area they needed to work on.  Liz and I are excited to continue the work in this building and continue to follow up with the middle and high school.

column48:
The Collaborative Teams of the Middle School/High School met in the High School library at 2:00.  The agenda for this meeting included two major topics.  The first was the data that placed them in Targeted status.  The focus was on how the data was generated and what steps must be taken to correct the current status.  It was noted that the data comes from the MPI and that a total of 125 IEP students were included in the data with 15 of those students scoring at Below Basic.  Discussion ensued on steps to take.  The first semester, the Middle and High School teachers focused on steps they could take in all classrooms to improve ELA scores for the 19-20 assessment.  It was noted that math has already met the improvement goal for the first year and that they must maintain or improve in that area as well as improve in ELA.  

The Superintendent spoke about their current CSIP, which was the second major topic discussed,  and stated they were in the process of researching and developing a new plan which would take effect in June 2020. 

Teams worked together for the rest of the meeting to determine the outcome of Effective Teaching Practices with which they were working and to develop next steps for the building.

column48: Once monthly the BLT meets and leads data team meetings in the elementary building.  During the meeting, three or four grade levels are discussed.  An agenda is provided and she takes minutes of each meeting.  They discuss successes they are having in the classroom.  Struggles are discussed and possible solutions are offered by members of the team.  The participants discuss the strategies they are using.  At this meeting they also discussed the iReady data results from the end-of-semester testing.  Concerns raised centered on the decision to reward students who met their target score with a movie and to reward students who raised their score but did not meet their goal with special classroom activities.  This group also chooses a "shared instructional objective" at each meeting.  Last year, the focus stayed on vocabulary throughout the K-6.  This year their goals are more varied and also encompass goals in ELA.

column48:
The purpose of this visit was to touch base and plan for the rest of the 2020-21 school.  The principal stated she did not want to try to start anything at this time due to Covid-19 in the fall and now they are looking at MAP/EOC testing, planning for that testing (which she has not experienced), additional quarantines of students.  We discussed meeting in late May to plan for the 2021-22 school year as it relates to DCI.  The thought was to begin serious work on DACL, plan those dates, and then schedule walk-throughs and feedback opportunities.

I asked about Data Teams this year and she stated they hadn't done any because there was no data to team around.  As a result, I asked if they are giving formative assessments of any kind and she stated "not a lot".  It is my feeling that focusing on DACL will open the door to further discussions around CFAs and the necessity for providing teachers and students information for goal-setting through the use of formative assessments.
column50: Make a plan in May for the work to begin in earnest next fall.

column48:
We had a good discussion as to what DACL was and how it could help their building. We worked on trying to come up with next steps but were not able to clearing define what that should be. Asst. Principal kept referring back to CPP(Consume, Process, and Produce). Wanted to make sure that our process would fit this because the HS staff were all doing this. One of the teachers did not feel this was happening like the  AP did but we did acknowledge his point. 

They had concerns about too many initiatives happening at one time and looking for how this might fit with them. Felt like some teachers might  be unwilling to buy in since they have been told many things with no follow through in the past and would not want to invest in one more thing like that. 

They do not seem eager to begin something else. The social studies teacher did however really liked what he was hearing and would like to find a way to get it to work for them. The Principal keeps wanting proof that of this working in other similar districts. I am feeling like he thinks it is a good process but may have some concerns that it would be the right fit for him and his staff at this point. Even thought we talk about this be researched based process, he was still having a challenge getting to the point that it could work for him.
column50: Meeting with Admin to get on the same page as to what message we are going to send to staff before we do anything else with them.

column39:
This was an introductory meeting with the Superintendent, James Simmelink.  We discussed the make-up of the district, the number of teachers in each building and at each level, some of the challenges of a small district, and their transition from PLC to DCI.  We looked at the Practice Profiles as a general discussion of their intent and purpose.  Mr. Simmelink was not willing to go beyond that discussion without having the team available.  We discussed the team they currently have in place and then determined a date for the DLT meeting.  He shared their goals for the coming year:  Goal 1 is work with Collaborative Teams and Goal 2 is a focus on CFAs.  He noted that they need a solid curriculum, which is not in place in some areas.  

He noted that many of their teachers had gone through a Data Team training several years ago but stated most of those teachers are no longer with the district.  We briefly discussed the possibility of using the VPN to get the teachers trained in this area but no decisions were made.
column48: See previous.

column22:
According to their SAPP, they are in pretty good shape and their CWIS echoed that information.  It was noted that they need to work on the group processes and we were told they were aware they needed to have agendas, take minutes and save those so they are accessible.  After taking the SAPP last spring they began implementing procedures to correct this.  As a former PLC, much of this was already in place.

They had previously set two goals for the 2019-20 year.  Goal 1 was on the development of their Collaborative Teams.  Specifically they want to (1) Develop process for effective and focused collaborative team meetings; (2) Develop common purpose and goals for collaborative teams; and (3) Effectively utilize the team processes.
column24:
This is a goal for this district this year.  They plan to begin with identifying priority standards, unwrapping standards and then writing learning targets.  Hopefully some of this work will begin in the second semester as the other work is completed.

This area was incorporated in their Goal 2.  They want to (1) develop clear and meaningful learning targets to guide instruction and student learning; (2) Create success criteria for learning targets; and (3) Construct quality assessment instruments which are of sound design and measure pre-determined learning targets.
column26: Because the elementary has more than one teacher at a grade level they have made more use of the DBDM process.  Time was spent discussing how this might work at the MS/HS where most of the teachers are singletons in their content area.  The change in State assessments has created a need for more focused attention on writing in the content areas.  This was discussed as a possible area for DBDM at the MS/HS as well as through the district.  No final decisions were made on this.

column48:
I've already shared much of what was discussed.  However, it is to be noted that the district is going to work as a district and not as two separate buildings.  As a result, all district staff will be trained on identifying priority standards and will begin that process during the PD day in October.  Many of the instructors at the MS/HS have curriculum maps but have not done the work of alignment, so it was felt this was a critical first step by the district.  Some of the elementary teachers already have identified some priority standards but will be reviewing and editing since the original work was done with the Common Core and just tweaked with the adoption of MLS.  At the elementary, they have determined their work will begin in the area of math. The MS/HS teachers will focus on their content areas.  

The MS/HS is going to work with developing and strengthening their Collaborative teams but the principal wants to do that work on their own.  It was suggested that he go into the VLP and look at that module and then assign it, or parts of it, to his teachers to view.  It was noted that they can do this independently or in small groups but specific details were left until he decides how to utilize the resource.

column48:
The North Nodaway District Leadership team met on January 28.  They began with a review of the original goals and thoughts that were developed in August 2019.  Those goals included the Development of Collaborative Teams, especially at the Middle School/High School, the preparation and use of CFAs, and the use of Data-based Decision Making, again focused on the Middle School/High School.
The DLT also had an opportunity to review and consider the CWIS in the new format that is available.  Some discussion followed.  A data review indicated:  
Elementary:  A low area was in reviewing CFA with teacher.  While the state average is also low, this is an area they would like to improve.
Leadership:  This was high in every category.  
Middle School and High School:  These buildings were lower than the elementary in all areas, due, in part, to the opportunity the elementary teachers had to have some of this training in the past.  The upper grades have no background in CFA or data teams and need that training.
Low areas on the CWIS included CFA and Data Teams.  It was discussed that in a small school, one or two votes in an area has much more impact than in a large school.  It was noted that teachers were not always sure what an indicator meant.
One of the areas which was mentioned as a concern was the tendency to collect data, but not to formally discuss and then use it.  An important area is determining what new steps to take when students aren’t successful, but that is not being discussed and then utilized as the DLT would like.
This spring, the CWIS will be taken as a district-wide group, with the various indicators being briefly introduced by the administration.  From there, the next steps in the process will be discussed.
It was proposed that next fall, two days be set aside for professional development which would focus on the DCI process.  By using two days, teachers could be given a solid foundation from which to begin building.  
For now, teachers at the middle school and high school will be given a one-half day introduction to Collaborative Teams and the process which has been found to be most effective.  This will be presented at the February 24 PD day beginning at 1:00.  On March 30, the entire faculty will gather to take the CWIS as described above.  
In the meantime, the instructional methods used at the middle school will be explored and suggestions offered for ways to improve or change that instruction.  The elementary plans to explore and eventually select a new math curriculum for next.

column22: This was a presentation based on the VLP module to introduce Collaborative Teams to the Middle School/High School teachers.  Reflections were shared and then provided to the newly hired principal for planning use for 20-21.
column48: The current high school principal shared at our January meeting that his teachers needed to start at the beginning and it was decided to begin their journey with Collaborative Teams.  The district is hoping to make a year-long plan for 20-21, but since the elementary has already had Collaborative Team training through PLC, I was asked to assist them at the upper grades.  This was quite simply an introduction.  As an addition, I provided the materials for them to work as teams (there are two identified teams in the MS/HS) to build a spaghetti tower.  I discovered that the teachers in this district are quite competitive.  Not only did they want to build the tower -- they wanted me to measure to see which tower was the tallest!  When we completed the activity, we discussed Pluses/Positives that they had discovered as they worked for the first time in their new teams.  We continued our reflections by discussing the Minus/Negative aspects of their teamwork.  Time was a big concern, as each team have seven or eight members who do not have similar planning times.  Finding a common topic was also discussed, with the idea of writing being something every class did being offered as a starting point.  Finally, we talked about things they might want to change, consider, etc. before beginning their serious teamwork next fall.  It was a great discussion.  The reflection sheets were shared with the new principal in an effort to provide him with notes from which to reflect and plan.

column48: Bruce and I visited with the middle school and high school teachers for the second time.  During this visit, teachers brought the CFAs they had begun to develop at our previous meeting and continued working on them.  We visited with each of the teachers, asking questions, offering suggestions, and proofreading their CFAs.  One of the most common misconceptions was that the CFA was strictly for the students.  We were able to point out that this helps the teachers know how to restructure their teaching to assist students to be most successful.  The CFA provides the teacher with time to reteach as needed prior to the summative assessment.  Because the next meeting is in February or March, the teachers were encouraged to submit their completed CFAs to Bruce and Myra for review and comment with the goal of giving one of them, if possible, prior to our next meeting.

column24: review of four prepared CFAs
column48: At our October 12 meeting, teachers were encouraged to submit two CFAs to Bruce and I for feedback.  Four CFAs have been submitted and feedback was offered today.  Two of the CFAs were math; one was science; one was social studies.  Feedback was offered through Google forms after Bruce and I had reviewed it.  Each teacher is to submit two CFAs for review and then use in the second semester.   Once taken by students, we will data team around the CFAs to determine how effective the CFAs were.   Teachers were encouraged to consider the rigor of the standard and to write items that at the very least come close to that level of rigor.  It is noted that the teachers actively included the vocabulary they had identified as necessary for understanding the teaching in their assessments which will allow them to locate misconceptions earlier in the unit.  While the next date is not determined at this time, it was suggested it would not be until February or March.  It was suggested that Bruce and I could come and meet with teachers on their planning times in an effort to give immediate feedback and to keep the process moving forward.
column50: Each middle school and high school teacher needs to submit 2 CFAs, give them to students, collect and evaluate them prior to a data team meeting in the spring.

column24: teachers brought CFAs in progress and completed to work on
column48:
This was the last scheduled visit for this school year at the middle and high schools.  The purpose was to review common formative assessments, to discuss the data to be collected, to make tentative plans for next year, and to offer feedback on CFAs as they were finished.  

Providing feedback was a large part of the morning's work.  The teachers worked to complete CFAs already started and then we reviewed the work, discussed possible edits that could be made, evaluated problem types in an effort to avoid low-rigor tasks, and made changes as needed.  The goal next year is to use the two CFAs requested from this year's work with students and to data team around those results.
column50: It was recommended that they give students the CFAs this spring, and either collect or copy student responses so there is data with which to begin next year's work.
column51: Finish providing feedback digitally on the CFAs that were completed.

column24: completed CFAs were submitted as copies or by emails for review and editing;  Ten CFAs were submitted for feedback.
column48: These CFAs were completed by the teachers and then submitted as copies and/or emails.  The purpose of this work was to review the CFAs and offer support by email.  As a result, feedback was provided by email to the teachers.  It is noted that at the middle school, the CFAs were submitted as multiple choice exclusively.  Most of those, according to the teachers, were taken from Evaluate, which is a benchmark type test given monthly by the district.  Suggestions for increasing the rigor were made.  In addition, short answer questions or open-ended statements were encouraged as a way to better determine what students know and/or understand, and as a method of determining where misconceptions may occur that need to be corrected.  Because this was after the final meeting set by the principal, all feedback was offered via email.  Copies of the emails were sent to the Early East Facilitator.

column24: Completed CFAs
column48: This was not a visit, per se, but coaching via email to assist in the development of CFAs to meet district goals.  The teacher had completed two CFAs in Algebra for her students.  It was noted that the questions centered around computation even though the topic was slope and graphing.  My responsibility was to offer suggestions, one of which was to get away from DOK 1 questions and move into more DOK 2 and 3 by asking students to observe and report.  Suggestions were made to not check students on all three solution strategies, but to focus on one at a time so the teacher could determine where misconceptions lie.  A variety of questions were suggested which could  be used to determine student understanding as opposed to just "finding an answer".  Also, encouragement was provided to ask students to justify their thinking and to compare one solution strategy to another.  My responses were then emailed to the teacher, the principal, and to my facilitator.
column49: As of this time, not until next fall.

I met with the superintendent and the special education director of the Pemiscot County Special School District (PCSSD).  There are 7 component school districts with which PCSSD works hires teachers to be placed in their buildings.  Currently there are four or these districts that are part of the MMD/DCI work.  Today's meeting was to determine if PCSSD wanted to become part of this work and assist in showing the benefits to the other three districts of working within this framework.  We reviewed all the materials including the blueprint, practice profiles, admin guide to coaching and step by step guide.  I also showed them the website and VLP potentials.  They were excited to become a part of the work and we have arranged for three different meetings with all the component districts to discuss how we can all work collaboratively to assist not only  the special education students in their buildings but how we can help ALL students.  These meetings will also include our compliance consultant, Tiffany Smith, as there may need to be some changes in how students will be identified and served.
It was decided that the teachers in all the component districts will have a separate login for PCSSD as well as one in the district in which they work to have VLP assignments and take thd CWIS and SAPP.  This will help PCSSD identify supports their teachers need in addition to those in each district.

They shared their dis-proportionality plans and ask for additional input to better explain how DCI will align and support their goals and plans to address dis-proportionality and non-compliance concerns.  Although the special education director has visited each district to discuss the compliance action plans and how to support each teacher and student, as a team we have plans to visit each component district, again, in April.  Our plan is to strengthen the alignment and support through the DCI framework and also bring the other 3 districts on board.

column22: In my sessions about SBG, we discussed that much of the work and decisions would actually be made in the collaborative teams already formed in MMD.
column24: We also discussed that the CFAs would be valuable evidence that could be used to track progress toward mastery of standards.  The fact that teachers were already able to create these assessments will make create summative assessments for SBG much easier and more efficient than if they had not had such a great background with MMD.
column26: The whole premise of SBG is making decisions based on data alone.  This can be such a challenge for teachers who are not accustomed to tracking data.  The MMD background with DBDM will really help make this process smoother.
column28: SBG requires teachers to really concentrate on what is essential to the grade level and district standards , thereby eliminating "fluff."  In order to provide effective reteaching and enrichment, while still moving forward with the new material requires skillful teaching and teamwork.  Effective teaching and learning practices will have to be a constant discussion and focus in collaborative teams and throughout all district PD.  This was a real concern among the teachers in my sessions.  It is very overwhelming to think of keeping all of these balls in the air without a lot of support!
column36: I made a concentrated effort to show the tie between what they had done through MMD and how that had really built a strong foundation for what they wanted to do with SBG.  It is a very natural progression.
column48: When I was first asked to come and speak about SBG, I was told I would be with intermediate elementary teachers.  This was ideal, as my background in SBG is only with elementary.  However, they ended up placing me with high school teachers due to scheduling conflicts.  It was okay, as my "presentation" was really only about how MMD had given the district a great foundation and jumping off point for the transition into SBG.  I then moved into some mindset shifts that would need to happen among all staff members for the transition to standards-based to be effective.  I will say that the MMD foundational piece of the session went very well.  All teachers and admin present seemed very well-versed in CT, CFAs, DBDM, and DACLs.  They all agreed that they were in a good place to make changes.  I had a really good feeling about that.  The shifts in mindset were a little harder for some of the classroom teachers, and I think part of the issue was that they really wanted to hear from a person who had a background with secondary levels.  They didn't so much want to wax philosophically as they wanted to know exactly how it would look and work.  The administrators who were present asked many good questions and seemed open to the idea of taking it slowly and working on building-up the teachers' background and understanding before pushing them to make changes.  I am hopeful that they will do that.  The move toward SBG is not an easy one, and teachers need to really believe in it and support it to make it work.
column49: None on the books, but the elementary and secondary principals did mention having me come back to do building-specific PD.
column50: K-4 has some subjects that are graded standards-based now, with the plan to slowly increase.  I was told that the goal is to move K-12 to SBG within 4-5 years. As I am not part of their cadre, I am unsure of what their MMD goals are, but they could easily align with this.

column48:
We had a good visit with Pierce City this afternoon to review their CWIS data.  The only Pierce City participants in the Zoom were Emily Scott, new elementary principal and Jennifer Graves, their contact person.  So, we were able to have a very candid conversation with them about their scores.  Their scores do not reflect a deep level of implementation, even in the foundational areas.  In fact, in many, many areas they are below the state average.

As you know, Jennifer is a rock, but she is leaving their district.  I recommended that she share this data with the superintendent, Dr. Kelli Alumbaugh, and point out the details in the CWIS data.  For example, they have teachers stating that they don't use state standards to align their assessment tools.  Some of their answers are alarming for reasons beyond the scope of our work.  She is planning to share this information with all of the administrators so that it will be used in planning for next year.

Considering that they are grossly below where I had hoped they would be, I would like to recommend that they stay in the Early Implementation Zone.  They will need to review those foundational modules again next year, and their CST will need to conduct walk-throughs and fidelity checks with their administrators. (We discussed all of this with Jennifer and Emily.)  I also think they need to be worked with in smaller groups than we were able to do this year.  We often presented to the entire faculty, and it obviously didn't reach them as we had hoped.  I explained to them that they might have to do rotating subs or do PD by building, and Shanna mentioned bringing their own data so that it can be analyzed - and they will see the power of the DCI model.
column50: They need to work on building a growth mindset with their staff so they are open to doing this work.  There are some culture pieces that are preventing them from moving forward.
column51: Set dates for training - but it needs to be in small chunks with smaller groups of teachers.

column39: DACL
column40: The teachers had DACL training earlier in the year so that they could see what ACL looked like in the classroom, since this is their 3 year goal.  Today's training was individualized to meet the needs of the staff based on conversations with teachers, administrators, and MMD/PLC consultants.  It was obvious through conversations shared during this training that the thinking is shifting from teachers believing they are to deliver information and the students are to learn it to teachers beginning to talk about creating learning situations that allow the students to come away with the skill, concept or thought through the coaching/feedback process.  This team is just getting started, but I am excited to hear how their thinking has changed since the beginning of the year.  Many of them have the will to make it happen.  The challenge will be for all of them, including the administrators, to realize it is a process that takes time.

column32: I observed a vertical team of 1st-4th grade teachers at Lake Road Elementary as they observed a 3rd grade teacher teach text features to a small group of 3rd graders.  Afterwards, the teachers gave feedback on how the instruction impacted student learning.  They call this peer coaching "Genius Round."  Then in the afternoon, we used another peer coaching strategy in mathematics, called "Teacher Time-Out."  This was done for 30 minutes in each 1st-4th grade classroom.
column48: This building (Lake Road Elementary) received peer coaching training in the fall of 2018 and this was my first time back to observe how implementation was going. column28: Developing Assessment Capable Learners:  each building team met with the District Leadership Team.  The DLT presented the overview of DACL.  This gave the DLT opportunities to practice the Overview, to receive feedback, and to explain how the BLTs would be involved at the professional development meeting planned for early January.
column48: The Ralls County DLT is comprised of the building principal and assistant principal from each building.  The focus this year is on covering the DACL modules.  The DLT plans to present the overview at the PD planned for early January with table leaders being provided by the BLTs.  The DLT presented the Overview to each BLT throughout the day.  This was to practice the presentation, try activities, make minor adjustments as needed, and to identify possible challenges or misconceptions.  My role was to support, offer suggestions, clarify meaning, and model activities as needed.  As we went through the day, struggles were identified and clarified.  Each activity in the module was done in full, but we discussed at length how to run it with the entire faculty present.  (Only 5 BLT were identified from each building.)  In the second round, I modeled how to do a Snowball activity with the human bar graph and we discussed how best to share the data.  By the third round, many of the challenges had been ironed out.  Discussion led to the conclusion that teachers would be assigned a table in an effort to mix the grade levels.  They felt this would lead to better discussion as each building has unique issues and concerns.  Before each group finished, the expectation that the group would be responsible for one of the other modules was discussed and modules were chosen.  The plan is to present one module in February, March and April.  The PD day in February is the 19th.

Today was a continuation of the CFA work that was started in September.  We worked on CFAs with the 6-8 grade teachers completing the math standards.  We are continuing to work in grade spans to do this work so that the common assessments are created collaboratively and at the appropriate depth of rigor for the standard for the grade level.  
The projection is that we will complete this work in math at the end of the month and begin ELA second semester.  
The teachers have been great to work with.  They are excited about the work.  More than one of them has shared on various occasions that for the first time they feel like they really have an understanding of what the standards mean and what mastery for each standard would look like and how this knowledge and mental model will change their instruction.  They also express appreciation for planning the work with the teachers a grade level above and below them so that they understand the big picture.

column48:
Today we worked with the 6th-8th grade teachers to determine success criteria and determine the skills and concepts that they agreed needed to be formatively assessed toward each priority standard in science.  This conclude this work with this span of teachers.  They have now completed this work in math, ELA, and science, and have the state cross-walk for social studies/ELA. 
All of the other grade levels in the building have completed this work in math, ELA, and have the social studies/ELA crosswalk from the state.  Science is the only content area they are lacking. Plans are being made to do the science with the elementary teachers.  The teachers are anxious to build units of instruction using the rigorous priority standards they have selected. They have proficiency scales created for Level 3 and 4 for each priority standard that gives an example of the success criteria for each level.  The intention of this district is to move to standards-based report cards.  
This building of teachers has been remarkable to work with.  They are eager to learn.  Considering that we started at the beginning of this year with DACL, the teachers see the value in the work of collaborative teams, CFAs.  They also understand that they will use DBDM with their formative assessments next year to help them determine how their students are progressing toward a standard rather than only relying on a benchmark assessment, such as STAR.  
Working with Dana and her teachers at Raymondville this year has been a pleasure!

column48:
I provided feedback on the DACL walk-throughs that Cynthia and I did in both elementary buildings the week prior to this date.  There was definitely lots of positive feedback; however, the core of DACL was not seen on a regular basis.  Most of the time today was spent on working together to seek to understand what their strengths were and where the gaps were.  One thing that was determined was that the teachers had a lot on their plates this year including a new ELA program that was very intensive and it's implementation very different than the way they were used to teaching. It was also suggested that even though they had DACL training last year, they really hadn't made implementation a priority.  One principal was out of town for this PD, so we left several options on the table.Those we discussed is as follows: 
1.) Perhaps they need to spend some time working on the learning progressions for each priority for each grade level which would allow the teachers to understand where they are going and the steps to getting there. (This would include some CFA work.) Then, they could share this information with the students so that they could determine their level of learning. 
2.) If or once the learning progressions are in order, I could train on each DACL quesion seperately.  Then, allow time for them to implement in their classrooms and use peer coaching to increase success. I would continue to train on the last two questions following the same process.
3.) Maybe a combination of 1 and 2.

I was so impressed with their desire to want real data and to want to implement DACL with fidelity, even if that meant going back and closing a gap that they hadn't realized until now.  I shared with this staff that this way of thinking is truely what an Assessment Capable District would do.  It is a priviledge to work with this district.

We used an adapted DACL Classroom Walk-Through Tool & visited 14 classrooms specifically looking for Teacher/Classroom Evidence of: 
Students create evidence of their understanding
Examples of ongoing and fluid assessment of student progress are present (thumbs up/thumbs down, think-pair-share, random student call-outs, personal white boards, discussion)
Examples of students keeping track of their learning progress are present (notebooks, charts, checklists, folders, web-based portfolios)
Room arranged for easy sharing
Room easy to move around in
Learning targets where students can see and teachers/students can refer
Resources aimed at supporting students’ understanding of their progress (Anchor Charts)
 -and-
Student evidence (in relation to learning targets):
Use rubrics to assess, improve their work and identify next steps
Use instructional tools (e.g. discussion techniques, hand signals, personal white boards, desk arrangement) that encourage feedback with peers/teacher
Share understanding with peers and teacher
Use vocabulary and phrases indicating self-assessment of work and progress 
Use data to set learning goals (“Where am I going? Where am I now? How do I close the gap?”) 
Each teacher/classroom observed received written feedback & "30 second feedback" in which we copied and left for them to reflect on current practices

column48: The purpose of our meeting was to work on adding Early Learning to the current CFA module.  The face to face meeting was incredibly valuable.  Molinda Mitchell, from Waynesville Early Childhood Center, brought many resources that will valuable to consider adding to the module.  Carrie Holt, St. Charles Early Childhood Center, had some resources, too.  This was the first year this facility has been open which brought all of the preschools in the district into one building.  Carrie stated that her teachers aren't where they need to be yet with CFAs.  The collaboration and sharing between the two buildings was very positive.  We worked through the module on the VLP with some ideas being shared.  More will come at a later time.  Cheryl Stock, DESE, is leading this work.

Where are we now? 2. Where are we going? 3. How do we get there?  Lead into conversations about Monitoring and Support needs
column38: This was an Admin Retreat and all DLT Admin were present.  Tied the MMD project into the District Mission/Vision of 1) RtI and 2) Student Support Goals.  Their 2 Big Rocks.  We did the overview and tied past and present MMD work back to each Big Rock so stakeholders see the connection to the work they already are doing.
column47: MAP Planning Template.  Shared a sample District Timeline for MMD Year 2 with District Contact.  Reviewed the Year 2 Invoice during the MAP Planning Template to support "where are we going?" and also the monitoring and support needed section.
column48: SCSD hosts an Admin Retreat each July.  This session was during a retreat day to help give an overview of the current status of their MMD work.  Brooke and Chris conducted the overview using the MAP Planning Template and elicited feedback from the Admin about next steps and monitoring and support needs they may have.  Discussed the Year 2 Invoice and what services our team can provide to support the Districts' Two Big Rocks (RtI and Student Support).  Made it clear this work is about processes that should be used in all content areas.

column26: Pockets of DBDM, but it was obvious through this training, that their is work to be done.
column48: Participants individually looked at the DBDM Practice Profile and marked where they were in the DBDM process and then met in groups to jot down strengths and opportunities for growth for each essential function.  Teams did a gallery walk and then shared out to the whole group, strengths that they noticed in each group's work that were the same and opportunities for growth that were similiar.  the theme seemed to be consistent...we collect lots of data, but then don't know what to do with it.  Participants looked at the CDT infographic for a refresher of what teams should look like/sound like and then did a quick connection on how CFAs also fit into the decision making process.  Participants were then led through the GAINS model with several times to reflect on their current work and possible next steps.  At the end of the training, each team reflected on what their next step(s) would be and left that for us.  Overall, it appears that the next step is common formative assessment for most teams.  The preschool team asked for follow up coaching as well.

column48: This was a collaborative meeting between two K-8 districts--Strain-Japan and Green Forest. They wanted to be able to meet with colleagues that shared the same setting and "show and tell" about MMD work.  The first work was sharing of the CWIS for each building and comparing their results to the district plan prepared several weeks ago to check for alignment. Other topics included SBIC, CFAs, portfolios and student-led conferences, and the VLP. The meeting took place after school from 4:30 to 6:30 p.m. at South Central RPDC.  All teachers and administrators attended.  I facilitated the discussion by introducing the topic, sharing opening questions, and then being the time keeper.  Each portion ended by doing a summary of key points, questions, and learning. The overarching goal was to share experiences and give feedback about implementation of the practices.  Teachers sat at tables in grade bands K-2, 3-5, and 6-8. Discussions were focused, lively, and productive. This was an example of CTE--teachers doing work that they believe will have an impact on student achievement.

column48: Today's purpose was twofold: We reviewed the results of the ACL walk-through that was done Dec. 3, reflecting on notes taken and overall picture of the building. We looked at the walk-through tool as a "practice profile" in action.  Coaching ensued as teachers noted areas of strength and celebration as well as areas that needed their attention next semester.  Several teachers cited the need to be more aware of saving anchor charts, having students do more charting of their performance and goal setting, and being proactive about essential questions that help drive daily learning targets. They also decided that the items on which they had concerns would be the perfect look-fors during their peer coaching opportunities. The second subject today was reflection using the CFA practice profile that started with a review of the essential functions, then collaborating as teams to find strengths and weaknesses in current assessment practice. Teachers shared ideas at tables about resources, alignment, and sharing practice items.
column50: Planning a focus for second semester on peer coaching after reflecting on today's findings.

column48: Coaching session had 3 main areas of focus.  Teachers reviewed the district implementation practice profile and responded individually, then shared collectively regarding current status.  Address two areas that they felt needed more attention; teachers want to do another DACL walk-through, and fine-tune it for their use, and they wish to deepen the use of technology in teaching and coaching. They would like to use these actions to respond to common issues they are see in student writing and made plans to revisit the current rubrics as well as share teacher-made questions that required a written response. Teachers then each created a Google Form with a QR code to post within their room so colleagues can scan the code, observe, and fill out the form, which will then be sent to the person being observed and the data can be aggregated. The technology grant was displayed on the Smartboard with input and suggestions from teachers as it was completed. Teachers also took the SAPP on DACL and coaching.

column48: Regular "Tuesday lunch" data team meeting was held with grades 2-3 sharing SRI performance data starting with Spring 2018 data. Plan is to next consider those results against MobyMax results and formative assessments to check for performance progress and alignment. Student growth over time was noted; teachers gave feedback based on their curriculum and alignment. Plan is to triangulate the above at the next meeting.  Last week was the end of third quarter with student-led conferences and celebrations. A first grade student conducted his conference with me; he chose several soup-can cutouts that had an unwrapped standard "I can" statement on it, and then demonstrate his ability to perform those tasks. This included skip counting, parts of speech, and finding the main idea. He was excited to be asked to share his learning. I then attended some junior high science fair demonstrations, during which students explained their goals, processes, results, learning, and how they would change their performance in the future: ACL in action!

column39: Using Technology to Support MMD
column48:
Jonathon and I met with teachers during their plan time to discuss efficient use of technology in the classroom to support MDD. We focused on two tools, Cast for Education and Screencastify. Both tools increase student engagement by allowing opportunity for visible thinking. Students can easily share their screen with their classroom teacher using Chrome for Education, while Screencastify allows both student and teacher to create video.

During lunch, Jonathon reviewed the new technology purchased via MMD Technology grant.  The iPad, Chromecast, and other tools were introduced. These tools will support SBIC.

column48: The purpose of this first visit was to introduce DACL to the staff of the elementary school and to then move into Part I of the module.  When asked, a handful of teachers indicated they used Learning Targets.  During this session we explored our own thinking.  We defined a DACL student, considered the three learning orientations, discussed learning targets in detail, and also worked with success criteria.  We considered the language used in learning targets and how that language can lead instruction. We used work from Missouri students to identify "look fors" and then used that list to examine and determine examples of strong and weak work.  The staff was very receptive and participated in all activities.

column48:
The purpose of this meeting was to plan for the 2019-20 school year.  Robyn wants to help her staff to see the connection of what the district is doing and how it connects to what they are doing in her building.  We worked on a plan for one of her back to school days.  She has chosen a "puzzle piece" theme to help with how things fit together.  She has great ideas in place as far as an icebreaker and teambuilder that will be used for reflection.  She will start with looking at the MMD big picture with the district focus.  This will include visiting the district mission and vision and teacher standards 1.2 and 5.2.  Next they will  look at the building mission and vision, DACL, and SBIC.  Dara, the lead teacher who was trained in SBIC, will share some highlights she has learned and implemented.  Next, they will look at the DACL Practice Profile and compare their building's vocabulary to the vocabulary used in the practice profile so everyone has a clear picture.  They will take the SAPP (possibly a paper copy) with jotting down their evidence as to why they are in a certain area.  Next they will do a "Notice and Wonder" to look at the district's "Teacher Goal Growth Guide" and the DACL Practice Profile.  Their last step will be to work on their goal for the district (Teacher Goal Growth Goal Guide), using the DACL practice profile.  They write a SMART goal on this guide.  The SAPP will be used for the data to show growth. 
 Their reflection will come through a teambuilder that they will end their day with.

column32: WOW!  Each building teacher leader shared what they are doing with peer coaching.  Each building is unique, but each one shared success!  FREEDOM ELEMENTARY-coaches are observing kindergarten classrooms to help them with interactive writing.  Teachers have growth goal plans...they are seeing the value in them and not as "just one more thing to do."  WILLIAMS EARLY CHILDHOOD-teachers are observing and coaching other teachers 2 times per month.  The principal shared very positive quotes from teachers which revealed their success with coaching.  She is sharing their peer coaching at the next school board meeting.  PARTRIDGE ELEMENTARY-shared a successful story from a 1st grade teacher on engagement.  WOOD ELEMENTARY-coaches are sharing the SBIC training with teachers and started coaching with some in the building.  THAYER ELEMENTARY-all teachers have observed others in the building and are leaving sticky notes on teacher's desks using the 30 second feedback format.  EAST ELEMENTARY-Teachers have recorded themselves using the swivel.  A follow up is for next week as teachers observe other teachers that are strong in the goals they have personally set.  HIGH SCHOOL-coaching has begun in 2 classrooms.  PINEY RIDGE-coach is observing behavior and relationship pieces and giving feedback.  CAREER CENTER-a coach shared that as an observer she went back and made notes of what she can do differently in her own classroom.  MIDDLE SCHOOL-two coaches went to observe the coaching process at Thayer Elementary.  They felt it was extremely beneficial to see it in action.  One 8th grade math teacher shared that she learned so much from watching a 2nd grade classroom.  She saw students being engaged and this has made her think that she needs to make some changes in our own classroom.

column48: There were several "Aha" moments in this 8th grade Math DBDM team meeting.  One:  teachers needed to "pre-take" the assessment to callibrate scoring and Two:  teachers needed to use agreed-upon instructional strategies with fidelity.  Overall, students gained proficiency in the CFA, but teachers found some areas that needed clarification with one another in grading.  There was also a discussion of chunking targets on the CFA vs. giving them practice being assessed with several targets in order to practice for MAP.  Shared the purpose of CFA with them again--to inform instruction, not give summative data. A closer look needs to  be taken with instructional practice vs. activities/assignments.  This is the first year that this team has practiced DBDM using MMD model.

column28: Lessons incorporating meta-cognition to elicit student thinking and reflection were modeled for students in the morning.  In the afternoon, teachers met as a group and were introduced to a variety of strategies to focus on meta-cognition, including silent teaching examples and daily routines (i.e. That's a Fact).  After each strategy was practiced, they then created their own examples.
column47:
NCTM's Eight Effective Teaching Practices in Mathematics (Note:  meta-cognition is one of the practices) 
John SanGiavanni's book - Daily Math Routines in Middle School Mathematics
column48: Our purpose was to show the importance of giving students time and space to think and share their thinking with others. When modeling, each class was given 1-2 tasks with a real life context that students engaged in for the entire 90 minutes.  Their past instruction has been very teacher centered and worksheet heavy.
column50:
Jan 2 will be a training on SBIC - Part 1

column47: NCTM Effective Teaching Practices for mathematics (metacognition is included in this resource)

column24: The Middle School and High School teachers worked in collaborative teams to determine the Big Ideas for the content areas of math, science, and social studies.  Within their groups they looked for gaps, provided clarification on what they were teaching, and identified learning targets for their students.  As this had been attempted but not completed in the past, the feeling was that much progress was made and work should continue along this vein.
column48: The educators in the three areas of mathematics, social studies and science collaborated to determine the priority learning standards for each grade level or course.  Gaps in instruction were identified as well as redundancies.  The goal was to begin determining a sequence of study that would lead to student success in each of these content areas.  (Reading is being covered by the Missouri Reading Initiative.)  They identified themes and then narrowed the focus to those themes considered most important.  Each content area achieved at different levels and work needs to continue in all three.
column50: For the Middle School and High School, this work needs to continue so they can begin development of CFAs.

column48:
The team reviewed the CWIS and the observations made by the general teaching population during the previous meeting.  Comments were made regarding taking the CWIS in the spring and working in groups to define the intent of each of the questions.  There was a general feeling that some of the results were inaccurate due to lack of understanding and clarification as well as new teachers taking the survey.  As this was taken before school started, several felt the new teachers would have had no idea and no experience with some of the statements.

Regarding data teams, it was suggested that during the data team process, teachers could share strategies and discuss what is or is not working with their students.  The suggestion was met with lack of enthusiasm as teachers did not appear to comprehend how this could work across content areas.  It must be noted that to my knowledge the Middle school and High School have not had actual training in data teaming, while the elementary did have the training as part of their CW work and had been using the Data Team process in monthly meeting the last three or four years.  I believe the training would be beneficial for the Middle School and High School.

The Superintendent provided a comprehensive and well-planned agenda.

column38: Alignment of writing focus standards and effective instructional strategies.
column40: With the disconnect between the K-5 and 6-12 ELA standards, the team also used the DESE scoring guides to help align their writing focus standards. This helped establish the alignment missing from the standards themselves and allowed for better articulation across grade levels. Next steps: compare and contrast actual student writing across grade levels, looking at low, average, and high examples to select anchors and to find strengths and weaknesses. Work will continue until teachers have created student-friendly scoring guides that students will be able to use to self-assess and for setting personal writing goals.
column50: Comments: No new material or training was done; my capacity was that of coach. The team is working to deepen implementation of ACL, especially in writing. Their goal is to increase student use of scoring guides for self-assessment and goal setting. They must articulate which standards they will focus on and how they will measure growth.
